# fedora — distro primer
#
# fedora is the upstream feeder for RHEL: a 6-month-cadence point-release
# distro maintained by Red Hat with heavy community involvement. each
# release is supported for ~13 months (current + previous), so you upgrade
# roughly once a year and have a 1-month grace window. fedora 44 (current)
# is supported through May 2026.
#
# default stack on a fresh Workstation install:
#
#   - GNOME on Wayland (Plasma + others are official Spins)
#   - btrfs root (since F33), with @ / @home subvolumes inside; ext4 still
#     an option in anaconda for those who pick it
#   - LUKS root encryption offered in the installer (off by default on
#     Workstation; some derivatives default to on)
#   - systemd everywhere
#   - NetworkManager
#   - firewalld (zone-based; FedoraWorkstation zone by default)
#   - SELinux ENFORCING (don't disable it; targeted policy is fine)
#   - PipeWire for audio (replaced pulseaudio as default)
#   - dnf5 from Fedora 41 onwards (native C++ rewrite of dnf4 — see [[dnf]])
#   - GRUB2 + BootLoaderSpec (per-kernel .conf files in /boot/loader/entries/)
#
# editions worth knowing:
#
#   - Workstation       — GNOME desktop. the default
#   - KDE Spin / Plasma — official KDE edition (promoted to Edition in F42)
#   - Server            — text-mode + cockpit web UI; xfs root (not btrfs)
#   - Silverblue        — immutable Workstation, rpm-ostree atomic updates
#   - Kinoite           — immutable KDE, same model as Silverblue
#   - Sericea / Onyx    — immutable Sway / Budgie
#   - CoreOS            — minimal, auto-updating, container-host focused
#   - IoT               — ostree-based, ARM/x86 for edge devices
#   - Spins             — XFCE, MATE, Cinnamon, LXQt, i3, etc.
#   - Labs              — purpose-built bundles (Astronomy, Robotics,
#                         Comp Neuro, Design Suite, ...)


RELEASE / UPGRADE
-----------------

# fedora is point-release. you upgrade in place between versions with the
# system-upgrade plugin (the supported path — DON'T just edit /etc/dnf/dnf.conf
# and `dnf upgrade` your way across, that's the partial-upgrade trap).

# refresh, install the plugin (already shipped on F41+), and pull the new
# release's packages WITHOUT applying them:
sudo dnf upgrade --refresh
sudo dnf install dnf5-plugin-system-upgrade        # F41+; on F40 it's dnf-plugin-system-upgrade
sudo dnf system-upgrade download --releasever=45   # pick the target release

# stage the actual upgrade — reboots into a special target that performs
# the rpm transactions, then reboots again into the new system
sudo dnf system-upgrade reboot

# what to do BEFORE the system-upgrade:
#   - merge .rpmnew / .rpmsave files in /etc:
sudo find /etc -name '*.rpmnew' -o -name '*.rpmsave'
#   - check release notes for known breakage:
#       fedoraproject.org/wiki/Releases/<n>/ChangeSet
#       discussion.fedoraproject.org (Common Issues thread)
#   - snapshot if you're on btrfs and have snapper / timeshift configured

# check current release:
cat /etc/fedora-release
rpm -E %fedora                                      # just the number

# remember: skipping releases is supported (F43 → F45) but not RECOMMENDED.
# the more versions you cross the more likely some package combination
# trips the resolver. one hop at a time is the safe path.


UPGRADE STRATEGY — STAYING SUPPORTED WITHOUT DAY-ZERO PAIN
----------------------------------------------------------

# fedora's release math gives you a wide window:
#   - 2 releases / year (~April and ~October)
#   - ~13 months of support per release
#   - so N-1 stays supported for ~7 months AFTER N releases (generous
#     overlap — use it)
#   - hard deadline: don't sit on a release once N+2 is announced. that's
#     when the EOL clock starts ticking hard.
#
# day-zero upgrades are voluntary risk. the only thing you actually
# HAVE to avoid is going EOL.


# THE T+8 RULE (recommended default)

# wait 8 weeks after a release before upgrading. by T+8:
#   - 1-2 kernel point releases have shipped (6.x.1, 6.x.2)
#   - DE patch releases (GNOME 47.1 instead of .0) have landed
#   - the worst third-party-repo lag has resolved
#   - the Common Issues thread has stabilized
#
# you give up ~2 months on the bleeding edge. you gain dramatically
# fewer "why did my system break" incidents.


# CALENDAR IN PRACTICE
#
#   fall release (~Oct/Nov)     →  upgrade in January   (past holidays,
#                                                        T+8-10 weeks)
#   spring release (~April/May) →  upgrade in June/July (T+8-10 weeks)
#
# this puts you on every release ~2 months after launch, ALWAYS one
# release ahead of EOL, never racing the clock.


# 5-POINT PRE-UPGRADE SANITY CHECK
# (run at T+8 weeks; if any item is red, wait 4 more and re-check)

# a) Common Issues thread is quiet for your stack:
#       https://discussion.fedoraproject.org/c/announcements/

# b) RPM Fusion ships for fedora N:
curl -sI https://download1.rpmfusion.org/free/fedora/releases/45/Everything/x86_64/os/

# c) akmod-nvidia is built for fedora N (only if you use nvidia — this
#    is the #1 cause of "I'm on a black screen after upgrade"):
dnf --releasever=45 list akmod-nvidia 2>/dev/null

# d) your critical COPRs have published for fedora N. check each at
#    copr.fedoraproject.org/coprs/

# e) your current install is healthy:
sudo dnf upgrade --refresh
sudo find /etc -name '*.rpmnew' -o -name '*.rpmsave'
sudo reboot                                    # confirm clean boot first


# UPGRADE — THE COMMAND SEQUENCE
# (only after the sanity check is green)

# 1. snapshot first — btrfs root + a manual snapshot gives you a
#    rollback path:
sudo btrfs subvolume snapshot / /.snapshot-pre-f45

# 2. system-upgrade plugin + download:
sudo dnf install dnf5-plugin-system-upgrade
sudo dnf system-upgrade download --releasever=45

# 3. apply (reboots into a special target, performs the rpm
#    transactions, reboots again into the new release):
sudo dnf system-upgrade reboot

# 4. verify post-upgrade. smoke test the things you actually use:
cat /etc/fedora-release                        # confirm version
lsmod | grep nvidia                            # if applicable
nvidia-smi                                     # if applicable
# launch your terminal, browser, dev toolchain, any niche apps.


# ROLLBACK IF SOMETHING BROKE

# btrfs rollback path (assumes you took the snapshot in step 1):
sudo btrfs subvolume set-default \
    $(sudo btrfs subvolume list / | grep '.snapshot-pre-f45' | awk '{print $2}') /
sudo reboot
# you're back on the pre-upgrade subvolume. promote it back to default
# permanently via `btrfs subvolume set-default` or by mounting the
# old @ and copying it back. this is exactly the openSUSE / Manjaro
# snapshot-rollback story, just hand-rolled instead of snapper-driven.


# SEQUENTIAL > SKIPPING

# fedora SUPPORTS skipping releases (N-2 → N) via:
#       sudo dnf system-upgrade download --releasever=N
# but the rpm resolver gets exponentially crankier with each version
# crossed. ALWAYS upgrade sequentially:
#       N → N+1 → N+2
# one extra hour, dramatically less --allowerasing debugging.
#
# if you've been off the grid and woke up on N-2:
sudo dnf system-upgrade download --releasever=$(( $(rpm -E %fedora) + 1 ))
sudo dnf system-upgrade reboot
# boot, verify, reboot to a clean state, repeat for the next hop.


# PRE-UPGRADE HARD RULES (apply to every upgrade)

# - DON'T upgrade with un-merged .rpmnew files. they carry forward and
#   bite you later. merge them on current release first.
# - DON'T upgrade from a non-default kernel. boot the standard
#   /boot/vmlinuz-<latest> first.
# - DON'T upgrade with a broken current install. fix the current release
#   first — dnf system-upgrade is not a recovery tool.
# - DISABLE third-party repos that don't ship for N yet (chrome COPRs,
#   vendor repos, etc.). re-enable after.
# - On nvidia: CONFIRM akmod-nvidia has shipped for fedora N before
#   pulling the trigger. (sanity check c above.)


# WHERE TO MONITOR

# - discussion.fedoraproject.org/c/announcements/  — official notes,
#   Common Issues per release. this is the canonical source.
# - fedoramagazine.org                             — readable summaries
# - bodhi.fedoraproject.org                        — see what's in
#   updates-testing if you want to peek ahead
# - fedoraproject.org/wiki/Releases/N/ChangeSet    — per-release
#   major changes
#
# RSS-subscribe at least the first two. the rest you check at upgrade
# time.


# WHAT THIS STRATEGY EXPLICITLY ACCEPTS

# - ~2 months behind early adopters on new features.
# - never bleeding-edge, never EOL — a permanent middle lane.
# - ~1 hour of effort every 6 months (sanity check + upgrade).
# - snapshot rollback path means worst-case recovery is minutes,
#   not a reinstall.


GRUB — SHOWING THE MENU, MANAGING KERNELS
-----------------------------------------

# fedora ships GRUB2 with two layers of menu-hiding stacked on top of each
# other, which is why "I want to see the menu on boot" is a recurring
# fedora question. the layers:
#
#   1. /etc/default/grub        — GRUB_TIMEOUT_STYLE / GRUB_TIMEOUT
#   2. grubenv `menu_auto_hide` — fedora-specific "hide if last boot OK"
#
# you have to defeat BOTH to get a reliable menu on every boot.


# THE FIX (do all three for a permanent visible menu):

# 1. edit /etc/default/grub:
sudo vi /etc/default/grub
#    set or add:
#       GRUB_TIMEOUT_STYLE=menu          (default: "hidden" — this is the key flag)
#       GRUB_TIMEOUT=5                   (seconds; -1 = wait indefinitely for input)
#       GRUB_DISABLE_SUBMENU=true        (flatten "Advanced options" so EVERY
#                                         kernel shows at the top level instead
#                                         of being hidden in a submenu)
#       GRUB_DEFAULT=saved               (default is "saved" — remembers your
#                                         last selection. 0 = always first entry)

# 2. regenerate grub.cfg. on fedora 34+ the path is unified for BIOS + UEFI:
sudo grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg
#    older UEFI installs may still use:
#       sudo grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/efi/EFI/fedora/grub.cfg
#    check which one exists on your system if the first command's output
#    looks too small.

# 3. disable fedora's auto-hide (the bit that hides the menu when the
#    PREVIOUS boot succeeded — independent of GRUB_TIMEOUT_STYLE):
sudo grub2-editenv - list                          # see current vars
sudo grub2-editenv - unset menu_auto_hide          # show menu every boot
sudo grub2-editenv - unset boot_success            # clear the "last boot ok" flag
sudo grub2-editenv - unset boot_indeterminate      # clear "boot uncertain" flag

# verify after reboot. if the menu still hides, check `boot_success` keeps
# getting set — it's written by the user-systemd unit grub-boot-success.timer
# (~2.5 minutes after login). mask it if you want to be extra sure:
systemctl --user mask grub-boot-success.timer


# ONE-SHOT SHOW MENU AT BOOT (no config changes):
#   - UEFI: hold/tap Esc (or F8 on some firmware) at POST
#   - BIOS legacy: hold Shift
# Shift on UEFI usually does NOT work — common source of "I tried shift and
# nothing happened". use Esc on modern hardware.


# UNDERSTANDING THE MENU ENTRIES — BootLoaderSpec:

# since fedora 30, GRUB entries are NOT generated into grub.cfg the old
# way. instead each kernel is a separate .conf file in /boot/loader/entries/.
# the kernel package install drops a file there; GRUB discovers them at
# boot. NO grub2-mkconfig needed when a new kernel lands.
ls /boot/loader/entries/
cat /boot/loader/entries/*.conf | head -30

# the format (one entry per .conf):
#   title    Fedora Linux 44 (Workstation Edition) (6.11.4-200.fc44.x86_64)
#   version  6.11.4-200.fc44.x86_64
#   linux    /vmlinuz-6.11.4-200.fc44.x86_64
#   initrd   /initramfs-6.11.4-200.fc44.x86_64.img
#   options  root=UUID=... ro rhgb quiet ...
#   grub_users $grub_users
#   grub_arg --unrestricted
#   grub_class fedora


# `grubby` IS THE TOOL for managing these entries (don't hand-edit):

# list every installed kernel entry
sudo grubby --info=ALL

# show just the default
sudo grubby --default-kernel
sudo grubby --default-index
sudo grubby --default-title

# set a different default
sudo grubby --set-default=/boot/vmlinuz-6.11.4-200.fc44.x86_64
sudo grubby --set-default-index=2

# add a kernel command-line argument permanently (writes to every entry
# AND to /etc/kernel/cmdline so future kernels get it too)
sudo grubby --update-kernel=ALL --args='quiet splash'

# remove an argument
sudo grubby --update-kernel=ALL --remove-args='quiet'

# remove a specific kernel entry (rare — usually let dnf handle it)
sudo grubby --remove-kernel=/boot/vmlinuz-6.10.3-200.fc44.x86_64


# KERNEL RETENTION — how many show up in the menu:

# fedora keeps the most recent 3 kernels by default. controlled by:
grep installonly_limit /etc/dnf/dnf.conf            # default: 3
#    bump it if you want more rollback options:
#       installonly_limit=5

# the rescue entry is generated once at install time as a special BLS
# entry — it's a kernel + initramfs frozen at install. don't expect it
# to track your current kernel. regenerate after a major upgrade:
sudo /etc/kernel/install.d/51-dracut-rescue.install add \
    $(uname -r) /boot $(uname -r)/initrd


# QUICK MENU INSPECTION:
sudo grub2-editenv - list                           # grubenv vars
sudo grubby --info=ALL | grep -E '^(index|title)='  # what the menu will show
ls /boot/loader/entries/                            # BLS entry files
cat /etc/default/grub                               # high-level config
cat /etc/kernel/cmdline                             # default cmdline for new kernels


# RECOMMENDED CONFIG for "show me everything, every boot":
#
#   /etc/default/grub:
#       GRUB_TIMEOUT_STYLE=menu
#       GRUB_TIMEOUT=5
#       GRUB_DISABLE_SUBMENU=true
#       GRUB_DEFAULT=saved
#
#   grubenv:
#       sudo grub2-editenv - unset menu_auto_hide
#
#   then:
#       sudo grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg
#       reboot


REPOS — OFFICIAL, RPM FUSION, COPR, FLATHUB
-------------------------------------------

# stock fedora repos cover free software only. enable these for the
# common "I want chrome / nvidia / mp3 codecs" needs:

# 1. RPM Fusion (free + nonfree codecs, multimedia, nvidia drivers):
sudo dnf install \
    https://mirrors.rpmfusion.org/free/fedora/rpmfusion-free-release-$(rpm -E %fedora).noarch.rpm \
    https://mirrors.rpmfusion.org/nonfree/fedora/rpmfusion-nonfree-release-$(rpm -E %fedora).noarch.rpm

# 2. flathub (cross-distro app sandboxing). fedora preconfigures a
#    filtered subset; add full flathub for everything:
flatpak remote-add --if-not-exists flathub \
    https://flathub.org/repo/flathub.flatpakrepo
flatpak remote-modify --enable flathub

# 3. COPR (community per-developer repos — same idea as the AUR, but with
#    binaries built on koji infrastructure):
sudo dnf copr enable user/project
sudo dnf install <pkg>

# multimedia codecs — the one-time setup most people want post-install:
sudo dnf swap ffmpeg-free ffmpeg --allowerasing
sudo dnf install gstreamer1-plugins-{bad-\*,good-\*,base} gstreamer1-plugin-openh264 \
    gstreamer1-plugins-bad-free-extras lame\* --exclude=gstreamer1-plugins-bad-free-devel


SELINUX — KEEP IT ENFORCING
---------------------------

# fedora's SELinux policy is mature. the right answer to AVC denials is
# almost never "permissive" or "disabled" — it's usually a missing label
# (`restorecon`) or a small policy adjustment (`audit2allow`).

# check status
sestatus
getenforce                                          # Enforcing / Permissive / Disabled

# investigate recent denials
sudo ausearch -m AVC -ts recent
sudo journalctl -b -t setroubleshoot

# auto-suggested fixes (read before applying)
sudo sealert -a /var/log/audit/audit.log

# common fix: relabel a file/dir to its policy-expected context
sudo restorecon -Rv /path/to/thing

# temporary permissive (next boot back to enforcing — useful for triage)
sudo setenforce 0

# DON'T disable in /etc/selinux/config unless you know exactly why.
# disabled SELinux means an unlabeled filesystem; turning it back on
# requires an autorelabel boot.


FIREWALLD — ZONE-BASED FIREWALL
-------------------------------

# fedora ships firewalld enabled with the FedoraWorkstation zone.
# day-to-day usage:

# show what's active
sudo firewall-cmd --get-active-zones
sudo firewall-cmd --list-all                        # default zone
sudo firewall-cmd --list-all --zone=public

# open a port — twice (--permanent for survival, no --permanent for live)
sudo firewall-cmd --add-port=8080/tcp
sudo firewall-cmd --add-port=8080/tcp --permanent

# or in one command with auto-reload
sudo firewall-cmd --add-port=8080/tcp --permanent && sudo firewall-cmd --reload

# allow a service by name (curated list in /usr/lib/firewalld/services)
sudo firewall-cmd --add-service=http --permanent
sudo firewall-cmd --reload

# zone assignment for an interface (default: tied to NetworkManager profile)
sudo firewall-cmd --zone=trusted --change-interface=virbr0 --permanent


NVIDIA DRIVERS — RPM FUSION PATH
--------------------------------

# fedora ships nouveau (the open-source nvidia driver) out of the box.
# nouveau works for basic display but is significantly slower than the
# proprietary driver and lacks CUDA, NVENC, and full vulkan support.
# the supported path to the proprietary driver is RPM Fusion's
# akmod-nvidia (auto-rebuilds against new kernels via akmods.service,
# conceptually like DKMS but RPM-native).

# this is the kind of setup you do once per machine and want to get
# right the first time. the order below matters — installing akmod
# before the kernel headers update, or rebooting before the akmod
# build finishes, are the two ways people end up at a black screen.


# STEP 1 — IDENTIFY YOUR CARD

# the right driver variant depends on your GPU generation:
lspci | grep -iE 'vga|3d|2d'

#   - akmod-nvidia                — CURRENT branch (570.x). supports
#                                   Turing (GTX 16xx, RTX 20xx) and newer.
#                                   ALSO works for Maxwell + Pascal on
#                                   the open-kernel build but check
#                                   rpmfusion's nvidia page if unsure.
#   - akmod-nvidia-470xx          — LTS 470.x branch. Kepler (GTX 6xx /
#                                   7xx) and older Maxwell. for cards
#                                   the current driver dropped.
#   - akmod-nvidia-390xx          — legacy 390.x branch. Fermi era
#                                   (GeForce 4xx / 5xx). end-of-life
#                                   upstream; only install if you have
#                                   nothing else.
#
# unsure which to pick: check nvidia's "Supported Products" page or
# rpmfusion's "Howto/NVIDIA". if `nvidia-detect` is installed, it
# picks for you:
sudo dnf install nvidia-detect && nvidia-detect


# STEP 2 — PREREQUISITES (EVERYTHING IN SYNC)

# RPM Fusion must be enabled (see REPOS section above). then:

# fully update first — you want the kernel and kernel-headers in sync
# BEFORE akmod tries to build against them.
sudo dnf upgrade --refresh
sudo dnf install kernel-devel-$(uname -r) kernel-headers-$(uname -r)


# STEP 3 — INSTALL THE DRIVER

# CURRENT BRANCH (most people):
sudo dnf install akmod-nvidia xorg-x11-drv-nvidia-cuda
#    xorg-x11-drv-nvidia-cuda pulls in the CUDA RUNTIME libs (libcuda),
#    needed for hardware video decode (NVENC/NVDEC), pytorch GPU,
#    blender CUDA render, etc. install it unless you specifically don't
#    want CUDA on the box.

# steam / proton / wine — pull 32-bit libs:
sudo dnf install xorg-x11-drv-nvidia-libs.i686

# legacy 470xx branch (substitute the package names):
sudo dnf install akmod-nvidia-470xx xorg-x11-drv-nvidia-470xx-cuda


# STEP 4 — WAIT FOR THE AKMOD BUILD

# akmods.service builds the kmod in the background. 5-15 minutes on
# typical hardware. DO NOT REBOOT until it finishes — booting with the
# kmod half-built drops you on nouveau (or worse, a black screen on a
# system where nouveau is already blacklisted).

# watch the build:
sudo journalctl -fu akmods.service

# verify the module file exists for your running kernel:
ls /lib/modules/$(uname -r)/extra/nvidia/
modinfo -F version nvidia        # prints driver version once built

# if `modinfo` says nothing, the build hasn't finished or it failed.
# kick it manually:
sudo akmods --force


# STEP 5 — SECURE BOOT (skip if disabled in firmware)

# check your state:
mokutil --sb-state                 # SecureBoot enabled / disabled

# if enabled: akmod's built kmod is unsigned and shim will refuse to
# load it. RPM Fusion's akmod hooks generate a Machine Owner Key (MOK)
# pair at /var/lib/dkms/mok.{pub,priv} and sign the kmod with it. you
# enroll the pub side once:
sudo mokutil --import /var/lib/dkms/mok.pub
#    sets a one-time password. on next reboot, shim's MokManager menu
#    appears BEFORE GRUB — pick "Enroll MOK", confirm with that
#    password. enrollment is permanent until you remove it.

# verify enrollment after reboot:
mokutil --list-enrolled | grep -A2 "DKMS\|nvidia"

# easier path (if you don't care about secure boot): disable it in
# firmware. matters less on a desktop than a laptop you carry out.


# STEP 6 — WAYLAND / KMS MODESET

# nvidia-drm.modeset=1 enables proper KMS support, required for clean
# Wayland sessions, smooth tty switches, and gnome / kde wayland on
# nvidia. driver 545+ enables this by default, and rpmfusion configures
# it via /usr/lib/modprobe.d/nvidia-modeset.conf. verify:
cat /sys/module/nvidia_drm/parameters/modeset       # should be: Y

# if it's N, force it. either add the modprobe option:
sudo tee /etc/modprobe.d/nvidia-modeset.conf <<'EOF'
options nvidia-drm modeset=1
EOF
sudo dracut --force
#    or add it as a kernel cmdline arg:
sudo grubby --update-kernel=ALL --args='nvidia-drm.modeset=1'


# STEP 7 — REBOOT AND VERIFY

sudo reboot

# after login, confirm:
lsmod | grep -E 'nvidia|nouveau'    # nvidia loaded, nouveau ABSENT
nvidia-smi                           # GPU model + driver version + processes
glxinfo | grep -i 'opengl renderer'  # should say NVIDIA, not llvmpipe

# session type (wayland or x11):
echo $XDG_SESSION_TYPE


# HYBRID LAPTOP / OPTIMUS — RENDER OFFLOAD

# for laptops with both Intel/AMD iGPU + nvidia dGPU, the modern model
# is "on-demand": iGPU drives the display, nvidia handles render
# offload per-app. saves battery vs running everything on nvidia.

# verify both GPUs are present:
lspci -k | grep -EA3 'VGA|3D'

# launch a single app on nvidia from a terminal:
__NV_PRIME_RENDER_OFFLOAD=1 __GLX_VENDOR_LIBRARY_NAME=nvidia glxinfo \
    | grep 'OpenGL renderer'                # should now say NVIDIA

# convenient wrapper:
sudo tee /usr/local/bin/nv <<'EOF'
#!/bin/sh
exec env __NV_PRIME_RENDER_OFFLOAD=1 __GLX_VENDOR_LIBRARY_NAME=nvidia \
         __VK_LAYER_NV_optimus=NVIDIA_only "$@"
EOF
sudo chmod +x /usr/local/bin/nv
#    then: `nv blender`, `nv steam`, etc.

# steam per-game launch options for nvidia render offload:
#     __NV_PRIME_RENDER_OFFLOAD=1 __GLX_VENDOR_LIBRARY_NAME=nvidia %command%


# CUDA DEVELOPMENT (vs CUDA RUNTIME)

# xorg-x11-drv-nvidia-cuda installs runtime (libcuda) only — enough to
# RUN cuda apps (pytorch, blender, ffmpeg-nvenc). for compiling cuda
# code you need the toolkit. two paths:
#
# a) nvidia's official cuda repo (most cuda versions, large download)
sudo dnf config-manager addrepo --from-repofile=https://developer.download.nvidia.com/compute/cuda/repos/fedora41/x86_64/cuda-fedora41.repo
sudo dnf install cuda-toolkit
#    fedora 44 isn't always in nvidia's repo on day one — substitute
#    fedora41 or fedora42 as a placeholder; the binaries are usually
#    forward-compatible. check developer.nvidia.com for current list.
#
# b) python-only path: install pytorch / tensorflow wheels that bundle
#    their own cuda libs. no system toolkit needed.


# COMMON FAILURES AND FIXES

# 1. "nvidia kernel module missing" / black screen after reboot.
#    you rebooted before akmod finished. boot to multi-user mode
#    (add `3` to kernel cmdline at the GRUB menu — that's why we
#    showed the GRUB menu earlier), log in, then:
sudo akmods --force
sudo systemctl isolate graphical.target
#
# 2. nouveau still loaded alongside nvidia. check the blacklist:
cat /usr/lib/modprobe.d/nvidia.conf
#    rpmfusion should drop a blacklist entry. if not:
sudo tee /etc/modprobe.d/blacklist-nouveau.conf <<'EOF'
blacklist nouveau
options nouveau modeset=0
EOF
sudo dracut --force
#
# 3. kernel update broke nvidia. akmod usually rebuilds on `dnf
#    upgrade`, but if it didn't fire:
sudo akmods --force --kernels $(uname -r)
sudo dracut --force
#
# 4. wayland tearing / glitching. driver 545+ should be fine. if
#    not, log out and pick "GNOME on Xorg" at the gdm session
#    picker — GNOME 47+ still ships the xorg session as an optional
#    package:
sudo dnf install gnome-session-xsession
#    KDE Plasma's wayland on nvidia is generally smoother than
#    GNOME's as of 2026.
#
# 5. screen tearing in X11. enable the nvidia force-composition
#    pipeline in xorg conf, or use a compositor (picom).
#
# 6. external monitor not detected after suspend. driver power
#    management quirk. on most setups this is fixed by:
sudo systemctl enable --now nvidia-suspend.service \
    nvidia-resume.service nvidia-hibernate.service


# REMOVAL / ROLLBACK TO NOUVEAU

sudo dnf remove '*nvidia*' --noautoremove
sudo dnf install xorg-x11-drv-nouveau          # if dnf removed it
sudo rm /etc/modprobe.d/blacklist-nouveau.conf 2>/dev/null
sudo rm /etc/modprobe.d/nvidia-modeset.conf 2>/dev/null
sudo dracut --force
sudo grubby --update-kernel=ALL --remove-args='nvidia-drm.modeset=1'
sudo reboot


SECURE BOOT — NOTES
-------------------

# fedora's shim is signed by Microsoft, so secure boot works out of the
# box for the default kernel and the shipped grub. third-party kmods
# (nvidia, virtualbox, dkms-built modules) need signing. options:
#   - disable secure boot in firmware (simplest, least secure)
#   - enroll a MOK and sign kmods (correct path; see above)
#   - use sbctl to manage your own keys (advanced)

# verify state:
mokutil --sb-state                                  # SecureBoot enabled / disabled
mokutil --list-enrolled


HARDWARE / FIRMWARE — fwupd
---------------------------

# LVFS (the linux vendor firmware service) is wired up out of the box.
# check / apply firmware updates from userspace, no reboot to firmware
# update utility:
fwupdmgr get-devices                                # what's reported
fwupdmgr refresh                                    # pull metadata
fwupdmgr get-updates                                # what's available
sudo fwupdmgr update                                # apply (reboots into UEFI for some)


FINGERPRINT READER (LAPTOPS)
----------------------------

# fedora's stack: libfprint (driver library) + fprintd (daemon) +
# authselect (PAM wiring). the biggest gotcha is hardware support —
# many recent laptops ship Goodix or Synaptics readers that need
# specific libfprint versions or third-party drivers. always verify
# support FIRST before installing anything.


# STEP 1 — identify the reader and check support
lsusb | grep -iE 'fingerprint|sensor|biometric'
# cross-reference vendor/product IDs at:
#   https://fprint.freedesktop.org/supported-devices.html


# STEP 2 — install fprintd (usually already on Workstation)
sudo dnf install fprintd fprintd-pam


# STEP 3 — enroll a finger
fprintd-enroll                                # default: right-index
fprintd-enroll -f left-index                  # specific finger
fprintd-list "$USER"                          # verify enrolled fingers
fprintd-delete "$USER" -f left-index          # remove one
# GUI path: Settings → Users → Fingerprint Login (toggle only
# appears when a supported reader is detected).


# STEP 4 — wire into PAM via authselect
# DON'T hand-edit /etc/pam.d/* on fedora — authselect manages PAM
# via profiles, and direct edits get overwritten.
sudo authselect enable-feature with-fingerprint
sudo authselect apply-changes
authselect current                            # verify the feature is on
# this adds fingerprint to sudo, su, login, GDM, and polkit. password
# remains the fallback if the reader fails or you cancel the prompt.


# STEP 5 — test
sudo -k && sudo true                          # should prompt for fingerprint
# then lock the screen (Super+L) and try GDM unlock.


# COMMON GOTCHAS

# 1. lsusb shows the reader but `fprintd-enroll` says "no devices".
#    libfprint doesn't support that exact revision yet. options:
#      - check upstream libfprint issue tracker for your USB ID
#      - try a newer libfprint from COPR if available
#      - for some Synaptics readers, the out-of-tree open-fprintd +
#        python-validity drivers exist (RPM build required; messy)
#
# 2. resume from suspend kills the reader. quick fix:
sudo systemctl restart fprintd
#    if it's persistent, file the kernel bug — there are open ones
#    for several laptop models, sometimes fixed by a firmware update
#    (worth running `fwupdmgr update` first).
#
# 3. Goodix 53xx family is hit-or-miss. some IDs (53b2, 5395, etc.)
#    are in mainline libfprint; others still need vendor patches.
#    check your specific ID against the supported-devices list, not
#    just "Goodix Generic".
#
# 4. fingerprint does NOT unlock LUKS. fingerprint kicks in only
#    post-boot (GDM, sudo, polkit). pre-boot biometric unlock isn't
#    a thing on linux. for hands-off boot, use TPM-backed unlock via
#    systemd-cryptenroll (see [[luks]] / the fedora-to-endeavouros
#    LUKS section) — different mechanism, different threat model.
#
# 5. multiple users: each user enrolls their own fingerprints. there's
#    no system-wide enrollment. enroll while logged in as the user.
#
# 6. disable / uninstall the wiring cleanly:
sudo authselect disable-feature with-fingerprint
sudo authselect apply-changes
fprintd-delete "$USER"                        # remove enrolled prints
sudo dnf remove fprintd-pam                   # optional


GNOME TIPS (Workstation default)
--------------------------------

# fedora ships GNOME on Wayland by default. xorg session is removable
# but still available — install gnome-session-xsession to add it back
# to gdm's session picker. KDE Plasma is its own Edition (and Spin);
# this section is GNOME-specific.


# MIDDLE-CLICK PASTE — the X11 PRIMARY workflow on GNOME

# how it works (built into GTK, no install / toggle needed):
#   - SELECTING text auto-copies to the PRIMARY selection. instant. no
#     Ctrl+C.
#   - MIDDLE-CLICK pastes from PRIMARY.
#   - Ctrl+C / Ctrl+V use a SEPARATE buffer (CLIPBOARD). the two
#     buffers don't overlap — selecting doesn't stomp your Ctrl+C
#     contents.
# this works on both Wayland and X11 in GNOME for native GTK apps.

# touchpad users — no physical middle button. two-finger tap maps to
# middle click via:
gsettings set org.gnome.desktop.peripherals.touchpad middle-click-emulation true

# firefox: check `about:config` → `middlemouse.paste` is true. it is
# by default on Linux builds; only a problem if you've imported a
# Windows profile.

# wayland-native apps that don't participate: a few Electron apps
# still miss primary-selection support. GTK / Qt / chromium all
# work. if a specific app misbehaves, that's a per-app bug, not a
# GNOME setting.

# vs code: enable selection-clipboard paste explicitly (it's on by
# default on Linux, but worth knowing):
#   "editor.selectionClipboard": true


# PTYXIS — the new default terminal (Fedora 41+)

# fedora replaced gnome-terminal with Ptyxis as the default terminal in
# Workstation 41. Ptyxis is GTK4 + container-aware (transparent toolbox /
# distrobox / podman integration) and uses VTE under the hood — same
# terminal widget gnome-terminal used. middle-click paste works by
# default for the same reason gnome-terminal's did.
#
# IMPORTANT: Ptyxis has its OWN Preferences dialog (hamburger menu →
# Preferences, or Ctrl+,). it looks visually identical to gnome-tweaks
# and other GTK4 settings panels — easy to confuse the two. terminal-
# specific settings (palette, font, scrollback, paste behavior,
# bell, container defaults, profile management) live there, not in
# tweaks.
#
# inspect Ptyxis's settings from the CLI:
gsettings list-recursively org.gnome.Ptyxis | grep -iE 'paste|scroll|bell'
#
# if middle-click paste DOESN'T work in Ptyxis (rare), the likely
# culprits — in order of frequency:
#   1. touchpad with no physical middle button → enable middle-click
#      emulation (gsetting above).
#   2. a tiling extension (Forge, Pop Shell) grabbing middle-click for
#      window management.
#   3. profile setting disabled — Preferences → Profiles → <name> →
#      look for paste / clipboard options.
#
# container integration is the new selling point: Ptyxis detects
# toolbox / distrobox / podman containers and offers them in the
# "New Tab" dropdown. no manual `toolbox enter` typing.
ptyxis --tab --container=<name>             # open a tab in a container
ptyxis --working-directory=/path            # open with a starting cwd

# if you preferred gnome-terminal and want it back:
sudo dnf install gnome-terminal
xdg-mime default org.gnome.Terminal.desktop x-scheme-handler/terminal
gsettings set org.gnome.desktop.default-applications.terminal exec gnome-terminal


# GHOSTTY — Mitchell Hashimoto's GPU-rendered terminal

# ghostty (1.0 released Dec 2024) is a Zig-built GPU-rendered terminal,
# native macOS app + GTK4 on Linux. it's in the same lane as alacritty /
# kitty / wezterm: performance-focused, less DE-integrated, cross-
# platform. NOT in Fedora's official repos. three install paths, in
# increasing friction order:

# 1. COPR (most common Fedora path — the closest analog to AUR or
#    ubuntu's snap for ghostty). updates flow via `dnf upgrade`:
sudo dnf copr enable pgdev/ghostty
sudo dnf install ghostty

# 2. flatpak from flathub. sandboxed; expect the usual flatpak caveats
#    (home-dir access via Flatseal, slightly slower first launch, some
#    $TERM / terminfo quirks at the sandbox boundary):
flatpak install flathub com.mitchellh.ghostty

# 3. build from source. you pay maintenance cost but get HEAD or any
#    pinned tag:
sudo dnf install zig gtk4-devel libadwaita-devel
git clone https://github.com/ghostty-org/ghostty.git
cd ghostty && zig build -Doptimize=ReleaseFast
sudo zig build install -Doptimize=ReleaseFast --prefix /usr/local

# canonical install instructions move over time. before relying on the
# COPR or flatpak ID above, sanity-check ghostty.org/download — it's
# the source of truth for current packaging.

# config lives at ~/.config/ghostty/config (single file, plain key=value).
# the doc page lists every option: ghostty.org/docs/config

# ghostty vs ptyxis: not an either/or. ghostty as a daily driver +
# ptyxis when you want quick toolbox/distrobox tabs is a common setup.
# set the default with:
xdg-mime default com.mitchellh.ghostty.desktop x-scheme-handler/terminal
gsettings set org.gnome.desktop.default-applications.terminal exec ghostty


# THE TWEAK STACK — what to install on day one

sudo dnf install gnome-tweaks gnome-extensions-app dconf-editor

# - gnome-tweaks         — top-level toggles GNOME upstream removed from
#                          Settings (fonts, window controls, startup apps,
#                          legacy extensions list, mouse acceleration).
# - gnome-extensions-app — manage installed extensions (enable/disable,
#                          configure, remove). counterpart to the
#                          extensions.gnome.org browser flow.
# - dconf-editor         — the regedit-equivalent for GNOME's settings DB.
#                          last resort when neither Settings nor Tweaks
#                          exposes the knob you need.

# fedora removes a few GNOME defaults you might want back:
sudo dnf install gnome-shell-extension-appindicator           # system tray icons
sudo dnf install gnome-shell-extension-caffeine              # inhibit suspend
sudo dnf install gnome-shell-extension-pop-shell             # tiling WM mode
sudo dnf install gnome-shell-extension-dash-to-dock          # macos-style dock
sudo dnf install gnome-shell-extension-just-perfection       # granular UI tuning


# EXTENSIONS — browser install vs dnf install

# two paths to install GNOME extensions:
#   1. dnf — packaged extensions, survive GNOME version bumps better,
#            update with the rest of the system. preferred where available.
#   2. extensions.gnome.org — browser-driven install. needs the
#            "GNOME Shell integration" browser extension AND the
#            gnome-browser-connector host (`sudo dnf install
#            gnome-browser-connector`). easier for things not in the
#            fedora repos.

# critical default-extensions-on-fedora to know about:
#   - background-logo-extension  — adds the fedora "f" watermark to the
#                                  desktop wallpaper. cosmetic. disable
#                                  via gnome-extensions-app if it bugs you.
#   - window-list                 — bottom taskbar; comes with the
#                                   "Classic" session, not standard.

# extensions DO break across major GNOME versions. fedora 44 ships
# GNOME 47; a fedora upgrade jumps GNOME too. check the extension's
# supported versions before a release upgrade — or just disable
# them all first and re-enable after.


# COMMON gsettings / dconf KNOBS

# show minimize + maximize window buttons (removed from GNOME default).
# this is the most-asked "where did my buttons go" GNOME question.
#
#   gnome-tweaks path: Tweaks → Windows → Titlebar Buttons → toggle
#                      Maximize and Minimize on. takes effect instantly,
#                      no logout needed.
#   gsettings path (same thing, scriptable):
gsettings set org.gnome.desktop.wm.preferences button-layout 'appmenu:minimize,maximize,close'
#
# the prefix before the colon = LEFT side; after = RIGHT side. swap
# for macos-style controls on the left:
#       'close,minimize,maximize:appmenu'
#
# CSD vs SSD caveat: most modern GNOME apps (Files, Settings, Text
# Editor, gedit, etc.) use Client-Side Decorations — they don't have
# a traditional titlebar, they put window controls inside the header
# bar. the button-layout setting controls that header bar too, so
# you'll get min/max buttons there. older GTK3 apps / Qt apps /
# Electron apps with Server-Side Decorations show the buttons in a
# traditional titlebar.

# disable mouse acceleration (gamers / pixel-art):
gsettings set org.gnome.desktop.peripherals.mouse accel-profile 'flat'

# disable natural ("reverse") scrolling on a normal mouse:
gsettings set org.gnome.desktop.peripherals.mouse natural-scroll false

# tap-to-click on touchpad:
gsettings set org.gnome.desktop.peripherals.touchpad tap-to-click true

# fixed (not dynamic) workspace count:
gsettings set org.gnome.mutter dynamic-workspaces false
gsettings set org.gnome.desktop.wm.preferences num-workspaces 4

# show seconds in the top-bar clock:
gsettings set org.gnome.desktop.interface clock-show-seconds true

# show battery percentage on laptops:
gsettings set org.gnome.desktop.interface show-battery-percentage true

# 12 vs 24 hour clock:
gsettings set org.gnome.desktop.interface clock-format '24h'

# disable animations entirely (perceived snappier, slightly less polish):
gsettings set org.gnome.desktop.interface enable-animations false

# dark mode:
gsettings set org.gnome.desktop.interface color-scheme 'prefer-dark'

# every gsettings command above has a Tweaks or Settings UI equivalent.
# use the CLI when you want reproducibility (a setup script you can
# rerun on a fresh install).


# FRACTIONAL SCALING (4K / hi-DPI displays)

# wayland fractional scaling is now stable in GNOME 47+. enable with:
gsettings set org.gnome.mutter experimental-features "['scale-monitor-framebuffer']"
# then Settings → Displays exposes 125% / 150% / 175% options.
# XWayland apps will look slightly softer (they render at integer scale
# and get downsampled); native wayland apps are crisp.


# WAYLAND vs XORG SESSION AT LOGIN

# fedora 44 defaults to wayland. you can pick "GNOME on Xorg" at the
# gear icon on the gdm login screen IF gnome-session-xsession is
# installed:
sudo dnf install gnome-session-xsession

# check current session type:
echo $XDG_SESSION_TYPE                  # "wayland" or "x11"
loginctl show-session $XDG_SESSION_ID -p Type


# GNOME SOFTWARE vs DNF

# GNOME Software (the app store GUI) backends:
#   - rpm packages from fedora repos (dnf under the hood)
#   - flatpak from flathub / fedora-flatpaks
#   - fwupd firmware updates
# for power users: stick to `dnf` for system packages, GNOME Software
# for flatpak apps and firmware. GNOME Software's rpm view sometimes
# hides packages that have no .desktop file or no metainfo XML.


# TOUCHPAD / GESTURES

# three-finger swipe for workspace switching is built in on Wayland —
# no extension needed. Settings → Touchpad shows the gesture options.
# on X11 you need `touchegg` to get the same gestures.

sudo dnf install xdotool ydotool        # if you want to script input
sudo dnf install gestures-shell-extension     # if you want extra mappings


# KEYBOARD SHORTCUTS

# Settings → Keyboard → View and Customize Shortcuts is the GUI. for
# scripting, the path is org.gnome.desktop.wm.keybindings + custom
# entries under org.gnome.settings-daemon.plugins.media-keys.

# add a custom Ctrl+Alt+T → launch gnome-terminal binding:
cat >/tmp/term-keybind.sh <<'EOF'
schema=org.gnome.settings-daemon.plugins.media-keys
custom=custom-keybindings
path=/org/gnome/settings-daemon/plugins/media-keys/custom-keybindings/custom0/

gsettings set $schema $custom "[\"$path\"]"
gsettings set $schema.custom-keybinding:$path name 'terminal'
gsettings set $schema.custom-keybinding:$path command 'gnome-terminal'
gsettings set $schema.custom-keybinding:$path binding '<Control><Alt>t'
EOF
bash /tmp/term-keybind.sh

# (Ctrl+Alt+T is not bound by default in GNOME — long-time linux users
#  often want it back. fun fact: there's no terminal hotkey at all
#  out of the box.)


# RESET TO DEFAULTS

# revert a single setting:
gsettings reset org.gnome.desktop.interface color-scheme

# nuke the entire GNOME config back to defaults (RUNS IN YOUR SESSION,
# logs you out cleanly):
dconf reset -f /org/gnome/


